This Flood Watch is being issued for Tallangatta Creek.

RENEWED RIVER LEVEL RISES ARE OCCURRING AND ADDITIONAL AREAS OF MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING MAY DEVELOP IN THE FLOOD WATCH AREA FROM SATURDAY AFTERNOON.

A low pressure system and trough will continue to move eastwards over Victoria today bringing rainfall and thunderstorms particularly about the eastern ranges with the potential for isolated heavy falls.

On Sunday a low pressure trough over inland NSW will extend over northern Victoria bringing the heaviest rainfall to the north east and far northwest. The system will push south over southern Victoria and Bass Strait bringing further widespread showers and rain for early next week.

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, many of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.

Renewed river level rises are expected and minor to moderate flooding may develop in the watch area from Saturday. In locations where severe thunderstorms develop, localised flooding due to heavy rain is possible. Catchments with existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see renewed flooding potentially to major flood levels from early next week at some locations. Renewed river rises are not expected to increase the currently forecast major flood peaks along the Murray River.

Major flood warnings from previous rainfall are current for the Murray and Loddon Rivers.

Moderate flood warnings are current for the Seven and Castle Creeks, Avoca, Goulburn, Kiewa, Ovens and King, Campaspe Rivers.

Minor flood warnings are current for the Mitta Mitta, Broken Creeks, Werribee, Barwon and Upper Murray Rivers.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 23/10/2022 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Barham to Wentworth.

Floodwaters from the Campaspe and Goulburn Rivers combined with flows down the Murray River have caused major flooding at Echuca and Moama. River levels at Echuca Wharf have exceeded the October 1993 flood (94.77 m AHD), with rises to 95.00 metres AHD possible.

As this flood water moves downstream, major flooding is possible at Swan Hill. Minor flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Wakool Junction and Boundary Bend, and possible at Mildura and Wentworth.

  • The Murray River at Swan Hill may exceed the minor flood level (4.50 metres) next week (27 to 30 Oct) and may reach the major flood level (4.70 metres) during the first week of November (2-5).
  • The Murray River at Wakool Junction may reach the moderate flood level (10.50 metres) around next week (27 to 30 Oct). The river level may reach around 11.00 metres during early November, with moderate flooding.
  • The Murray River at Boundary Bend may reach the moderate flood level (8.50 metres) during early to mid November.
  • The Murray River at Euston may reach the minor flood level (9.10 metres) during mid November. Further rises are possible.
  • The Murray River at Mildura Weir may reach the minor flood level (36.00 mAHD) during mid November. Further rises are possible.
Forecasts for Swan Hill and downstream along the Murray River will be refined once there is more certainty in the expected peak at Echuca Wharf, and other downstream locations.

A community meeting for Swan Hill and surrounding areas will be held this Monday, 24 October from 6.30pm at the Swan Hill Town Hall. Representatives from VICSES and partner agencies will provide information about the Murray River flood event and be available to answer questions. The community meeting will be live-streamed online via the Swan Hill Rural City Council Facebook page.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels online by visiting wwww.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings
  • Floodwater is dangerous - do not drive through floodwater. Do not overestimate the capability of your vehicle. It doesn’t take much to make your car become unstable, lose traction or wash away.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels may cause flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Some agricultural land may be vulnerable to flooding. Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Local roads may be closed.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area please check www.ses.nsw.gov.au in New South Wales and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 23/10/2022 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the along the river in the Emily Street area of Seymour.

  • Goulburn Broken Catchment Management Authority advise that rises are happening in the Goulburn River around the Emily Street area.
  • River levels at Emily Street were recently recorded as 6.0 m and slowly rising. The Goulburn River at Seymour is not expected to rise above 6.5 m. 
  • At about 6.1 m, a few houses in Emily Street are likely to flood.
Act now - take actions immediately to protect your life and property, and move to higher ground.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will leave for a safer place if it becomes necessary. 
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Be prepared to move household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Impacts in your area:  
  • A small number of properties are likely to be impacted and possibility become isolated 
  • Flooding above floor level of a few single-story homes may occur along Emily Street
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • You may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 23/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app

  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
For health information and support contact the below organisations: Lifeline on www.lifeline.org.au or phone 13 11 14. Beyond Blue on www.beyondblue.org.au or phone 1300 224 636. Kids Helpine on www.kidshelp.com.au or phone 1800 551 800. SANE Australia on www.sane.org or phone 1800 187 263.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Nathalia-Picola-Barmah and nearby areas.
  • Flooding is expected within the Nathalia, Picola and Barmah areas.
Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by increases in flooding.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • You can leave your home anytime if you feel unsafe.  
  • An emergency relief centre is open at Nathalia Community Centre, 42 Robertson Street, Nathalia.

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Turn off all switches at the main electrical switchboard, including the Main Switch. 
  • Unplug all your appliances and if you can, lift them up so they will remain clear of any floodwater that may inundate your property. 
  • Turn your solar system off at the inverter and then turn off at the switchboard (all switches on the switchboard should be in the OFF position).  
  • Turn solar batteries off. Follow the shutdown procedure which will be close to battery system. Do not attempt to disassemble the battery or open any of the panels. 
  • You should turn off your gas supply by locating your gas meter and turning the gas supply service valve to the “OFF” position by rotating the handle to so that it is horizontal. 
  • Before leaving, make sure all LPG cylinders are closed (clockwise to close the cylinder valve) at the valve on top of the cylinder. Do not disconnect any appliance unless the LPG cylinder is being relocated away from danger.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters (https://www.emv.vic.gov.au/responsibilities/victorias-warning-system/emergency-broadcasters/list) and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • You may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • Relocate your stock, fodder and machinery to higher ground if you have not already done so.  
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Yarra River to Coldstream and Downstream of Coldstream.

  • The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 20 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 24 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 21 October 2022. 
  • Rainfall totals of 1-3 mm in the upper part of the catchment and less than 2 mm for the lower part of the catchment are forecast for the rest of today, Saturday 22 October 2022.
  • The Watts River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 28 mm since 09:00 AM Friday 21 October 2022. Rainfall totals of 1-3 mm are forecast for the catchment for the rest of today, Saturday 22 October 2022.
  • Water levels of the Yarra River and Watts Rivers at various locations are rising in response to the rain. 

  • Watts River:
The level of the Watts River at Healesville is currently at 2.23 metres below the Minor Flood Level (2.80 metres) and rising. It is expected to peak below the Minor Flood Level (2.80 metres) this evening (Saturday 22 October 2022).

  • Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream:
The level of the Yarra River at Coldstream is currently at 3.14 metres, below the Minor Flood Level (4.00 metres) and rising. It is expected to peak around the Minor Flood Level (4.00 metres) tomorrow evening (Sunday 23 October 2022).

  • Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte:
The level of the Yarra River at Yarra Glen is currently at 3.19 metres, below the Minor Flood Level (4.10 metres) and rising. It is expected to peak around the Minor Flood Level (4.10 metres) tomorrow night (Sunday 23 October 2022).

  • Yarra River from Warrandyte to Abbotsford:
The level of the Yarra River at Heidelberg is currently at 4.42 metres, below the Minor Flood Level (6.00 metres) and rising. It is expected to peak around the Minor Flood Level (6.00 metres) tonight (Saturday 22 October 2022).
The level of the Yarra River at Alphington is currently at 2.07 metres, below the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres) and rising. It is expected to peak below the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres) overnight (Sunday 23 October 2022).
The level of the Yarra River at Abbotsford is currently at 2.27 metres, below the Minor Flood Level (2.70 metres) and rising. It is expected to peak above the Minor Flood Level (2.70 metres) tonight (Saturday 22 October 2022).

  • Minor flooding in the Yarra/Watts River catchment is expected to affect low-lying areas adjacent to the waterway including bicycle paths.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.

  • Renewed river rises are possible mid next week. You should stay informed of any further warnings or advice for the Campaspe River. 
  • If your buildings have been impacted by flood waters you should have your property inspected by a registered electrician. Visit the Energy Safe Victoria site for more: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/energy-safety-during-floods/
  • Beat the Bite: Be aware of the risk of mosquitos bring and cover up with long, loose-fitting clothing.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
Beat the Bite: Mosquito Alert    
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. 
Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/campaigns/beat-the-bite. What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.  
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin. 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 
Flood Recovery Hotline - Call 1800 560 760
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • navigating available supports
  • clean-up (visit the Campaspe Shire Council website for more: campaspe.vic.gov.au/Our-services/Emergency-management/Flood-event-2022)
  • temporary accommodation
  • mental health and wellbeing support
The recovery hotline is open from 7.30am-7.30pm everyday.
Need an interpreter? Call the hotline on 1800 560 760 and press 9.
For flood and storm information and support in NSW visit nsw.gov.au/floods

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Nathalia to Numurkah Broken Creek Floodplain..
  • MINOR FLOODING CONTINUING ALONG THE BROKEN CREEK AT WALSHS BRIDGE AND NATHALIA
  • Minor flooding will continue along the Broken Creek at Walshs Bridge and at Nathalia for the next few days.
  • River levels in and around Numurkah are expected to see rises similar to that of the December 2010 event in coming days.
  • Further rainfall is forecast from Friday. A flood watch is current, advising of the potential for renewed flooding.
  • Broken Creek:
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Broken Creek.
  • The Broken Creek at Walshs Bridge is currently at 2.53 metres and rising slowly, with minor flooding. The river level is likely to continue rising slowly above the minor flood level over the weekend.
  • The Broken Creek at Nathalia is currently at 1.68 metres and rising slowly, with minor flooding. The Broken Creek at Nathalia is likely to continue rising slowly above the minor flood level (1.50 m) over the weekend. A peak prediction will be provided once upstream peaks have been observed.
  • The Nathalia-Katamatite Road is open. Avoid the Walsh Road Bridge South and Walsh Road Bridge areas which area currently under active traffic management.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.

  • Health Messaging 
  •  Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants.  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  People’s private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home.   Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.     Flooding can cause sewage to overflow inside your home. This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour.

MAJOR FLOODING HAS EASED AT McCOYS BRIDGE
MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT SEYMOUR
MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT MURCHISON AND SHEPPARTON
Major flooding has eased along the Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge Saturday morning. The major flood peak along the Goulburn River is now downstream of McCoys Bridge and approaching the Murray River. Moderate flooding is continuing at Seymour and minor flooding is continuing at Murchison and Shepparton.
Further rainfall is forecast throughout Saturday and into early next week and renewed river rises are possible. The situation is being closely monitored and warning updates will be issued as required.
Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour:
Moderate flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour.
The Goulburn River Downstream (D/S) Lake Eildon is currently at 3.79 metres and steady, above the minor flood level. The Goulburn River Downstream (D/S) Lake Eildon is expected to remain above the minor flood level (3.00 m) during Saturday.
The Goulburn River at Seymour is currently at 5.50 metres and steady, with moderate flooding. 
Renewed river rises with moderate flooding are likely along the Goulburn River at Seymour from Saturday afternoon, but are expected to remain well below the major flood level.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Be prepared to move household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • If you are using a generator, do not attempt to connect it to the wiring of your home. This is dangerous and illegal.   
  • A generator should only be used outside, with an extension cord to supply power direct to appliances such as the fridge or freezer. Using a generator indoors creates a number of safety risks including the potential for carbon monoxide poisoning or a fire.
If you choose to leave early for a safer place
  • Ensure all electrical and gas-powered heating and cooking appliances are turned off. 
  • Turn off all switches at the main electrical switchboard, including the Main Switch. 
  • Unplug all your appliances. 
  • You should turn off your gas supply by locating your gas metre and turning the gas supply service valve to the “OFF” position by rotating the handle to so that it is horizontal.
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
  • Due to recent rainfalls roads have significantly deteriorated, drive with extreme caution.   
  • Animals are taking refuge on roadways, drive with caution and remain vigilant of wildlife. 
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Recovery:
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • Register for clean-up on private property 
  • Navigating financial and other support 
  • Access to temporary accommodation Mental health and wellbeing support 
The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 (press 9 to speak to an interpreter)
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
When you have been advised it is safe to return
  • Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property. 
  • If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician. 
  • If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician. 
  • For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/

Health Impacts
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants.  
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.   
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home.  
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Flooding can cause sewage to overflow inside your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so contaminated areas must be cleaned and disinfected.
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away  including canned and packaged foods.

This updated Emergency Warning is being issued for Kerang. If you are in this area, you should evacuate immediately.

Current advice from the Bureau of Meteorology (BOM) is that the Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge is not expected to peak until tomorrow (Sunday). Now that the peak has been delayed, people in Kerang are able to evacuate to Swan Hill via one of two routes, depending on their location.

The levee west of the Loddon River and south of the Murray Valley Highway has been overtopped and has now breached in some areas. People in this area should evacuate immediately via the updated route below.

The levee east of the Loddon River is experiencing significant seepage but has not been overtopped and is unlikely to breach. People in this area should evacuate immediately or risk being isolated for at least 24-36 hours once the Loddon River peaks.

  • The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge was at 77.97 mAHD at 11am Saturday morning and rising slowly, with major flooding (major flood level is 77.80 mAHD).
  • The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge is likely to reach around 78.00 metres Saturday evening. Further rises are possible to around the January 2011 flood peak of 78.03 mAHD during Sunday.
If you are located in Kerang, it is recommended you evacuate immediately.
The above evacuation routes may be closed with little or no warning if they become unsafe, due to the rising floodwater. If you do not evacuate before this time, your property may be isolated and it may be too late to leave.

You should travel to a safe location:
  • The relief centre that has been opened in Swan Hill at the Swan Hill Basketball Stadium at 15 Gray Street.
  • Family or friends’ homes located in a safe location, away from flooding.
If you are located west of the Loddon River, south of the Murray Valley Hwy and east of Boort-Kerang Rd the safest evacuation route to Swan Hill is via:
  • the Kerang-Quambatook Road to Quambatook
  • turn right onto the Quambatook-Swan Hill Road
  • turn right onto the Donald-Swan Hill Road
  • turn left onto the Murray Valley Highway.
If you are located east of the Loddon River the safest evacuation route to Swan Hill is via:
  • the Kerang-Murrabit Road
  • turn left before Murrabit onto Murrabit W Road
  • turn left onto the Benjeroop-Lake Charm Road
  • turn right at Lake Charm onto the Murray Valley Highway.
When you leave:
  • Follow directions given by Victoria Police and emergency services. Pay attention to road closed signs and stay on the safe evacuation route.
  • Be aware of driving hazards such as water over roads, mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees.
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater.
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone and medications.
If you stay:
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you.
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story.
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation and know your plans.
Evacuating too late or choosing to remain in your home when recommended to evacuate is dangerous and may put your life at risk.

You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Based on historic data, this flood is likely to have a similar impact as the January 2011 flood, which resulted in flooding in properties surrounding Kerang and isolation of the Kerang township.
  • Areas may lose services including power, water, sewerage and phone coverage. You may also lose nbn services due to flooding. For more information on nbn access during an emergency, visit www.nbnco.com.au/learn/what-happens-in-a-power-blackout/emergencies-and-outages
  • Snakes may look for shelter and food inside houses, storage sheds and other buildings near floodwater. Damaged structures and debris are more accessible to snakes.
  • In the 24 hours to 9am Saturday, rainfall totals of 10 to 30mm were recorded in the upper Loddon catchment. Further rainfall is forecast for next few days. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
  • River levels are elevated along the Loddon River downstream of Kerang.

This Flood Watch is being issued for the Ovens and King River Catchment.

RENEWED RIVER LEVEL RISES ARE OCCURRING AND ADDITIONAL AREAS OF MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING MAY DEVELOP IN THE FLOOD WATCH AREA FROM SATURDAY AFTERNOON    

A low pressure system and trough will continue to move eastwards over Victoria today bringing rainfall and thunderstorms particularly about the eastern ranges with the potential for isolated heavy falls.

On Sunday a low pressure trough over inland NSW will extend over northern Victoria bringing the heaviest rainfall to the north east and far northwest. The system will push south over southern Victoria and Bass Strait bringing further widespread showers and rain for early next week.

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, many of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.

Renewed river level rises are expected and minor to moderate flooding may develop in the watch area from Saturday. In locations where severe thunderstorms develop, localised flooding due to heavy rain is possible. Catchments with existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see renewed flooding potentially to major flood levels from early next week at some locations. Renewed river rises are not expected to increase the currently forecast major flood peaks along the Murray River.

Major flood warnings from previous rainfall are current for the Murray and Loddon Rivers.

Moderate flood warnings are current for the Seven and Castle Creeks, Avoca, Goulburn, Kiewa, Ovens and King, Campaspe Rivers.

Minor flood warnings are current for the Broken Creeks, Werribee, Barwon and Upper Murray Rivers.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.

This Warning is being issued for Bogong Village and Falls Creek.

  • This Warning replaces the Warning issued at 6:21 PM on 21/10/2022.
  • A landslide has occurred on the Bogong - High Plains Road area at Bogong Village.
  • There is a slow moving active landslide on Bogong High Plains Road in the area near Spring Saddle Track above Bogong Village.
  • After recent heavy rainfall, cracking has been identified in the area around Spring Saddle Track and debris has been moving from below the track onto the Bogong - High Plains Road.
  • Potential flash flooding has been forecast which could result in imminent failure which could pose a threat to life of road users. 
  • The Road will be closed to all traffic - with the exception of Emergency services personnel until further notice
  • Following further inspection the road may be reopened to local residents, essential services and emergency services. 
  • This road will remain closed to the general public for at least 30 days. 
  • Falls Creek Village is accessible by Bogong High Plains Rd via Omeo
Stay safe by avoiding damaged buildings, fallen trees and powerlines, blocked or damaged roads. Be aware of other hazards caused by the landslide.
What you should do:
  • If you have chosen to remain, please monitor the road conditions. 
  • If another landslide occurs, act quickly.
  • If you are outside when a landslide occurs, move quickly and keep clear of embankments, trees, power lines and poles.
  • If you are inside, move to the part of building that is furthest away from the approaching landslide and take shelter under a table or bench.
  • Stay away from the impacted area to allow emergency services to help affected communities.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters  and monitoring warnings.

Driving:
  • Plan your trip in advance - travel may take longer due to closed roads and poor driving conditions.
Impacts in your area:
The landslide has resulted in:
  • Fallen trees and branches.
  • Dangerous road conditions.
  • Mud and debris on the road.
  • There will be no public access to Falls Creek and Bogong Village as the Bogong - High Plains Road for at least the next thirty days. 
  • The Bogong High Plains Road on the other side of Falls Creek is now open to local traffic

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal.

MAJOR FLOODING HIGHER THAN THE 1993 FLOOD OCCURRING AT ECHUCA AND MOAMA, WITH A MAJOR FLOOD PEAK AROUND 95.00 METRES AHD POSSIBLE FROM SUNDAY EVENING.
Floodwaters from the Campaspe and Goulburn Rivers combined with flows down the Murray River have caused major flooding at Echuca and Moama. River levels at Echuca Wharf have exceeded the October 1993 flood (94.77 m AHD), with rises to 95.00 metres AHD possible during Sunday into Monday, with major flooding.
As this flood water moves downstream, river level rises and significant major flooding is expected at Torrumbarry and Barham. Forecasts for Swan Hill and downstream along the Murray River will be refined once there is more certainty in the expected peak at Echuca Wharf, and other downstream locations.
Flood operations are being conducted by the Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) at Hume Dam to manage inflows from the upper Murray, Mitta Mitta River and other tributaries. MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and WaterNSW to plan release strategies.
Further rainfall is forecast over the weekend into early next week, which may cause renewed river level rises and flooding. This situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be issued as necessary.
Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal:
Minor flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Albury and Tocumwal. Moderate flooding is occurring at Corowa.
The Murray River at Albury is currently at 4.44 metres and steady, with minor flooding. Renewed rises are possible, with forecast rainfall.
The Murray River at Corowa may reach around 6.20 metres late Saturday into Sunday, with moderate flooding. Renewed rises are possible, with forecast rainfall.
The Murray River at Tocumwal peaked near 6.90 metres around 10:00 pm Tuesday and is currently at 6.50 metres and slowly falling, with minor flooding. Renewed rises are possible, with forecast rainfall.

Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.

Much of the flooding impacts is occurring on the NSW side of the Murray River

Murray River - Emergency Area - Leave and Do Not Enter  Authorised by : Paul Lyddiard, Incident Controller, Southern Zone 

As a result of the dangerously high level of the Murray River and flood warnings remaining for the many tributaries that drain into the Murray River, the NSW State Emergency Service advises that the following areas of the Murray River are an emergency area under the State Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act): 
  • downstream of Tocumwal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge. 

Under section 22 of the SES Act people are directed as follows: 
  • Leave the emergency area 
  • Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users of the rivers.  No boats can enter the emergency area and people cannot enter the area for any recreational purpose such as fishing or swimming.  
  • Emergency Services, Roads and Maritime Services and council personnel are permitted to access the emergency area for emergency operations and enforcement.   

This takes immediate effect, and remains in place until the area is no longer deemed to be an emergency area. 

For further information contact: NSW State Emergency Service on 132500.

Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.

Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move immediately to higher ground, away from waterways.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off all switches at the main electrical switchboard, including the Main Switch. 
  • Unplug all your appliances and if you can, lift them up so they will remain clear of any floodwater that may inundate your property.
  • Turn your solar system off at the inverter and then turn off at the switchboard (all switches on the switchboard should be in the OFF position). The solar system will have information on shut down procedures. 
  • Turn solar batteries off. Follow the shutdown procedure which will be close to battery system. Do not attempt to disassemble the battery or open any of the panels. 
  • You should turn off your gas supply by locating your gas meter and turning the gas supply service valve to the “OFF” position by rotating the handle to so that it is horizontal. 
  • Before leaving, make sure all LPG cylinders are closed (clockwise to close the cylinder valve) at the valve on top of the cylinder. Do not disconnect any appliance unless the LPG cylinder is being relocated away from danger.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters (https://www.emv.vic.gov.au/responsibilities/victorias-warning-system/emergency-broadcasters/list) and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • Parks, tracks and campgrounds maybe closed due to flooding
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
  • Local roads may be closed due to impact of flood waters. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 23/10/2022 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
For health information and support contact the below organisations: Lifeline on www.lifeline.org.au or phone 13 11 14. 
Beyond Blue on www.beyondblue.org.au or phone 1300 224 636. 
Kids Helpine on www.kidshelp.com.au or phone 1800 551 800. 
SANE Australia on www.sane.org or phone 1800 187 263.

The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Register Find Unite - Red Cross  
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
People need to be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.

  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
  • If you are using a generator, do not attempt to connect it to the wiring of your home. This is dangerous and illegal.   A generator should only be used outside, with an extension cord to supply power direct to appliances such as the fridge or freezer. Using a generator indoors creates a number of safety risks including the potential for carbon monoxide poisoning or a fire.  
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Health Messaging
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants.  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  People’s private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home.   Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.     Flooding can cause sewage to overflow inside your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so contaminated areas must be cleaned and disinfected.  Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away  including canned and packaged foods.   It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.
  • Recovery: 
  •  Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: navigating available supports mental health and wellbeing support The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 If your home is flooding and you need emergency assistance Call 000 If your home is about to flood Call VICSES on 132 500

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for the Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang.

Major flooding is occurring along the Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang.

  • The Loddon River at Downstream (D/S) Loddon Weir is currently at 4.65 metres and steady, with minor flooding. 
  • The Loddon River at Appin South peaked at 3.47 metres on 7.00 am on Friday. The river level is currently at 3.42 metres and steady, with major flooding. The Loddon River at Appin South is expected to remain above the major flood level (3.30 m) overnight Saturday into Sunday. 
  • The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge (Kerang) is currently at 77.88 m Australian Height Datum (AHD) and steady, with major flooding (major flood level is 77.80 m AHD). The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge (Kerang) is likely to reach around 78.00 metres overnight Saturday into Sunday. Further rises are possible to around the January 2011 flood peak of 78.03 m AHD during Sunday
In the 24 hours to 10:00 pm Saturday, rainfall totals of up to 35 mm were recorded in the upper Loddon catchment. Further rainfall is forecast for next few days. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary. 
If you are located in this area you should act now to protect yourself and move to higher ground.

Leaving now is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - do not drive through floodwater. Do not overestimate the capability of your vehicle. It doesn’t take much to make your car become unstable, lose traction or wash away.
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • The Loddon Valley Highway is closed south of Kerang.
  • The Murray Valley Highway is closed north of Kerang.
  • The levee west of the Loddon River and south of the Murray Valley Highway has overtopped and has breached in some areas.
  • The levee east of the Loddon River is experiencing significant seepage but has not been overtopped and is unlikely to breach.
  • Some areas are likely to lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
  • Be aware that snakes may look for shelter and food inside houses, storage sheds and other buildings near floodwater. Damaged structures and debris are more accessible to snakes.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/campaigns/beat-the-bite

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Leitchveille, Gunbower, Patho, Torrumbarry. 

  • The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir as at 7pm Saturday 22 October measured 7.83m, at  the major flood level (7.8m).
  • Significant work has been undertaken to improve the serviceability of the Torrumbarry levee.
  • The Torrumbarry Weir may reach around 7.85 metres around 24-27 October. Further rises are possible.
For commercial and recreational users of the Murray River: NSW State Emergency Services have declared an emergency area on the Murray River for areas downstream of Tocumal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge under the state Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act). Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users. Visit the NSW SES website for information: https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/news/all-news/2022/emergency-area-declared-murray-river/
Act now - take actions immediately to protect your life and property, and move to higher ground.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Beat the Bite: Mosquito Alert    
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/campaigns/beat-the-bite. 
What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.  
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin. 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 
Impacts in your area:  
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding. 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Snakes can lose their home during a flood. As a result, they may look for shelter and food inside houses, storage sheds and other buildings. Damaged structures and debris are more accessible to snakes. For more information check the Better Health website (betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/After-a-flood-animal-and-insect-related-hazards)

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa.

  • RENEWED MODERATE FLOODING EXPECTED AT KIALLA WEST OVERNIGHT SATURDAY. MINOR FLOODING PEAKING AT EUROA. 
  • Minor flooding is occurring at Euroa, Kialla West, Strathbogie, Galls Gap and Telfords Bridge. 
  • Renewed moderate flooding is expected at Kialla West overnight Saturday into Sunday. Additional rises are possible with further rainfall over the weekend.
  • In the 24 hours to 4:00 pm Saturday, rainfall totals of up to 45 mm have been observed across the Seven and Castle Creeks catchment.
  • Further rainfall is forecast into Sunday.
Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa:
  • Renewed moderate flooding is expected along the Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa.
  • The Seven Creeks at Kialla West is currently at 4.86 metres and steady, with minor flooding. The Seven Creeks at Kialla West is expected to reach the moderate flood level (5.00 m) Sunday. Further rises are likely on Monday. 
Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 23/10/2022 11:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Health Messaging 
  •  Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants.  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  People’s private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home.   Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.     Flooding can cause sewage to overflow inside your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so contaminated areas must be cleaned and disinfected.  Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away including canned and packaged foods.   It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

This Emergency Warning is being issued for parts of Echuca and Echuca Village. 
If you live, work or are holidaying in this area, you should Evacuate Immediately. 

MAJOR FLOODING HIGHER THAN THE 1993 FLOOD OCCURRING AT ECHUCA AND MOAMA, WITH A MAJOR FLOOD PEAK AROUND 95.00 METRES AHD POSSIBLE FROM SUNDAY EVENING.

MURRAY RIVER
  • Major flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Echuca, Moama, Torrumbarry, Barham.
  • The Murray River at Echuca is at 94.80 metres AHD and rising at 3pm Saturday 22 October. This level is similar to the October 1993 flood event (94.77 m AHD). 
  • The river level may peak around 95.00 to 95.2 metres AHD overnight Sunday into Monday, with major flooding.

CAMPASPE RIVER
  • Moderate flooding is continuing along the Campaspe River at Echuca. At 4pm Saturday 22 October, the Campaspe River at Echuca measured 94.5m AHD, the same level as at 12pm.
  • Further rainfall is forecast over the weekend and on Monday. A flood watch is current, advising of the potential for renewed flooding.
  • Flooding may impact residents whose properties surround the Campaspe River. 

For commercial and recreational users of the Murray River: The NSW State Emergency Service have declared an emergency area on the Murray River for areas downstream of Tocumal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge under the state Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act). Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users. Visit the NSW SES website for information: https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/news/all-news/2022/emergency-area-declared-murray-river/
If you are located in the warning areas, it is recommended you Evacuate Immediately. If you do not relocate now you may become isolated for a number of days. If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. The EVACUATION ROUTE is currently open but may not stay that way.

The Bendigo Emergency Relief Centre (Bendigo Showgrounds) is being utilised as primary relief centre for the area. People should expect there may be a requirement to be moved to Bendigo from Echuca Emergency Relief Centre (Echuca South Basketball Stadium).
What you should do: 

Travel to a safe location. Options include: 
  • Travel to family and friends outside of the impacted area.
  • Travel direct to Bendigo Relief Centre, Bendigo Showgrounds, Holmes Road Bendigo.
  • If assistance is required to travel, please attend Echuca South Basketball Stadium, 244 High Street, Echuca South.
  • For evacuation route follow this link: Evacuation Route
If you are travelling by car: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 
If you stay:  
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 

For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Evacuating too late or choosing to remain in your home when recommended to evacuate, is dangerous and may put your life at risk. 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur. 
  • Areas near the affected location may lose services including power, water, sewerage and phone coverage due to flooding.
  • Some residents may notice their toilets aren’t flushing or sinks aren’t draining as normal. Please consider minimising water use, including the use of washing machines and dishwashers, and limit baths and showers. This will to reduce the volume of water being sent to sewer while flood levels are high.
  • Snakes can lose their home during a flood. As a result, they may look for shelter and food inside houses, storage sheds and other buildings. Damaged structures and debris are more accessible to snakes. For more information, check the Better Health Website.

Beat the Bite: Mosquito Alert 
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/campaigns/beat-the-bite. What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.  
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin. 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications - if you do not, phone 132500 for urgent assistance.

  • Minor flooding is occurring at Euroa and Kialla West. Renewed moderate flooding is likely at Kialla West Sunday evening.

  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants.  
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • People’s private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home.     
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.
  •  Flooding can cause sewage to overflow inside your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so contaminated areas must be cleaned and disinfected.  
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away including canned and packaged foods.   

  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Campaspe River Downstream of Rochester.

Moderate flooding is continuing along the Campaspe River at Echuca. Further rainfall is forecast from Monday into early next week and renewed river rises are possible.

Campaspe River downstream of Rochester: 
  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River downstream of Rochester. 
  • The river level along the Campaspe River at Echuca at 8am Sunday 23 October was 94.53 m AHD and above the moderate flood level. 
  • The river is expected to remain around the moderate flood level (94.40 m AHD) for the remainder of Sunday. 
  • Renewed rises are likely in coming days due to flood waters backing up from the Murray River and are expected to continue in the coming days.
A community newsletter current from Saturday 22 October is available here: https://files-em.em.vic.gov.au/public/CommNews/Community-Newletters/Community_Newsletter_-_Loddon_Mallee_Floods_-_22_October_2022.pdf?v=202210230940
Echuca has been impacted. If you are located in this area you are in danger - act now to protect yourself and move to higher ground. 

Leaving now is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous. Follow this link for latest Evacuation Route.

A relief centre is open at Bendigo Showgrounds, Holmes Street, Bendigo.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if needed.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations.
  • Widespread flooding of the area.
  • Homes and towns are likely to be isolated.
  • Some areas will be likely to lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding. 
  • Damaged structures and debris are more accessible to snakes. For more information, check https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/After-a-flood-animal-and-insect-related-hazards
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 23/10/2022 06:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Beat the Bite: Mosquito Alert     
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/campaigns/beat-the-bite.  

What you can do: 
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.   
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin.  
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune into ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
